–1305","1257–1295":"1257–1295","1200–1272":"1200–1272","about 1260":"about 1260","about 1272":"about 1272","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1305":"1305","ABT 1272":"about 1272","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1257":"1257","1268":"1268","1322":"1322","1200":"1200","ABT 1245":"about 1245","about 1230":"about 1230","Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","meanings":["A name corrpted from Hannah, q.v. It is also found several times in a male name. From Ann, Anne, we have as nicknames Nan and Nancy"],"variants":[{"name":"Nancy","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. From the 18th century it is clearly used as a pet form of   Ann   (  see  Nan  ), but it may originally have been a similar formation deriving from the common medieval given name   Annis  , a vernacular form of   Agnes .  Nowadays it is an independent name, and was especially popular in America in the 1930s, 40s, and 50s."]},{"name":"Nan","meanings":["Originally a pet form of   Ann   (for the initial <i>N-</i>,  compare  Ned  ). It is now also widely used as a short form of   Nancy ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne de Beaumont was born about 1230, in France, her father, Thibaut de Beaumont Comte, was 32 and her mother, Jeanne de Senlis Dame de Luzarches-la-Motte, was 32. She married Aubert II de Longueval about 1260. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died about 1272, at the age of 44."},"et":{"about 1230–about 1272":"umbes 1230–umbes 1272","1230–1272":"1230–1272","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","–1322":"–1322","–Male":"Surnud","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1257–1295":"1257–1295","1200–1272":"1200–1272","about 1260":"umbes 1260","about 1272":"umbes 1272","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1305":"1305","ABT 1272":"umbes 1272","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1257":"1257","1268":"1268","1322":"1322","1200":"1200","ABT 1245":"umbes 1245","about 1230":"umbes 1230","Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","France":"Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1230–about 1272":"noin 1230–noin 1272","1230–1272":"1230–1272","1268–Female":"1268–Kuollut","–1322":"–1322","–Male":"Kuollut","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1257–1295":"1257–1295","1200–1272":"1200–1272","about 1260":"noin 1260","about 1272":"noin 1272","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1295":"1295","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1272":"1272","1305":"1305","ABT 1272":"noin 1272","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1257":"1257","1268":"1268","1322":"1322","1200":"1200","ABT 1245":"noin 1245","about 1230":"noin 1230","Longueval, Somme, Picardie, France":"Longueval, Somme, Picardie, Ranska","France":"Ranska"},"fr":{"about 1230–about 1272":"environ 1230–environ 1272","1230–1272":"1230–1272","1268–Female":"1268–Décédée","–1322":"–1322","–Male":"Décédé","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1250–1305":"1250–1305","1257–1295":